With key interaction features from input 1, we generate an IDG at an updated time t (Fig. 2 step (2)), which is a directed acyclic graph used as a people’s connection model. We treat each node in the IDG as a person, and each directed edge as a spreading relation between two people who stayed at the same location for a certain time. The direction of the edge means the infection source-destination, which is defined so that the arrow points to the person who left a place later since he/she is more likely to be infected by the other who left earlier. With input 2, we label people’s states in the IDG, and update the previous IDG in incubation period \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
